The test is asserting that chained suffix expressions on an object member (`c.l[0..1]`, `c.l[t_i]`) behave like doing the member lookup into a local first. It fails on the slice case at line 25. I’ll inspect the parser/codegen path for index expressions and then run under gdb around those functions to see how the suffix expression is represented.

---

The failure is an assertion rather than a crash, and it occurs at the first issue-101 test: `return c.l[0..1]` produces something other than `[0,1]`. The relevant parser/codegen path is suffix expressions (`.` and `[]`). I’ve found a suspicious order in `package_suffix`: it materializes the index/key before materializing the container object. If the key expression uses registers and the object expression is itself a suffix (`c.l`), evaluating the object can free/reuse the key register before the final `GETIDX` instruction is emitted. I’ll inspect the exact expression descriptor state in gdb.

---

The first failure is exactly the nested suffix case from issue #101: `c.l[0..1]`, while the same slice through a local (`l2[0..1]`) passes. I need inspect register allocation/freeing and bytecode generation for ranges, because nested suffix descriptors (`ETMEMBER` used as the container of a later `ETINDEX`) are represented compactly and may lose their object type/index across packaging. Since gdb appears to have only minimal symbols, I’ll use source plus runtime debug/disassembly facilities if available.

